Key Findings
Kebumen Regency recorded the highest poverty rate in Central Java at 17.83%.
Wonosobo and Brebes also showed relatively high poverty levels, exceeding 17%.
Semarang City had the lowest poverty rate at 4.56%.
Salatiga City and Jepara Regency were among the regions with the lowest poverty levels.
The average poverty rate in Central Java was 11.39%.
Significant disparities exist between regions with high and low poverty rates.

Discussion:
The analysis reveals noticeable differences in poverty levels among regions in Central Java. Several factors may contribute to these disparities, including economic structure, urbanization, employment opportunities, educational attainment, infrastructure availability, and access to public services.
Urban areas generally experience lower poverty rates due to greater economic diversification, better infrastructure, and broader employment opportunities. Meanwhile, some rural regions continue to face challenges related to economic productivity and income generation.
Understanding these differences is essential for designing effective poverty reduction programs and promoting balanced regional development.

Conclusion:
The results indicate that poverty levels in Central Java varied considerably across regencies and cities in 2021. Kebumen, Wonosobo, and Brebes were identified as the regions with the highest poverty rates, while Semarang City and Salatiga City recorded the lowest rates.
These findings highlight the importance of targeted poverty alleviation policies, equitable economic development, and improved access to education and employment opportunities to reduce regional disparities and enhance social welfare throughout Central Java.

